\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
MBON neuron parameters
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
LIF Neuron Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We used the conductance based LIF model to model the MBONs.
 The LIF neuron equation is as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tau_{m}\frac{dV}{dt}=(V_{rest}-V(t))+g_{ex}(E_{ex}-V(t))+g_{inh}(E_{inh}-V(t)).
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Box Frameless
position "t"
hor_pos "c"
has_inner_box 1
inner_pos "t"
use_parbox 0
use_makebox 0
width "100col%"
special "none"
height "1in"
height_special "totalheight"
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Here V is the membrane potential of the neuron as a function of time , 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{m}$
\end_inset

is the membrane time constant, 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{rest}$
\end_inset

is the resting membrane potential, 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{ex}$
\end_inset

is the excitatory reversal potential and 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{in}$
\end_inset

is the inhibitory reversal potential.
 The synaptic conductances are expressed by 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{ex}$
\end_inset

 (excitatory) and 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{inh}$
\end_inset

 (inhibitory).
 They are modelled according to the following equations:
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tau_{ex}\frac{dg_{ex}(t)}{dt}=-g_{ex}(t)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Box Frameless
position "t"
hor_pos "c"
has_inner_box 1
inner_pos "t"
use_parbox 0
use_makebox 0
width "100col%"
special "none"
height "1in"
height_special "totalheight"
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
and
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tau_{inh}\frac{dg_{inh}(t)}{dt}=-g_{inh}(t),
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{ex}$
\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{inh}$
\end_inset

are the synaptic time constants for the excitatory and the inhibitory conductanc
e, respectively.
 When the neuron receives an action potential from a presynaptic cell the
 postsynaptic conductance increases by the following formulas: 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{ex}\rightarrow g_{ex}+\Delta g_{ex}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{inh}\rightarrow g_{inh}+\Delta g_{inh}$
\end_inset

 for excitatory and inhibitory synapses, respectively.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The three-factor plasticity learning rule
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We introduce an STDP (Spike-Timing Dependent Plasticity) learning rule into
 our model has been observed in the locust mushroom bodies (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Cassenaer:2007go"

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Synaptic change in our model is the result of dopamine concentration value
 multiplied by synaptic tag value at each time point.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Synaptic weight change is gated by the presence of dopamine.
 Eq.
 2.9 shows that weight change occurs when dopamine concentration is above
 0
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\text{d}w_{ij}(t)}{\text{d}t}=D(t)c_{ij}(t).
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Weight change requires both the the dopamine concentration and the synaptic
 tag to be different from zero.
 We model the DA neuron as an integrate and fire neuron which determines
 the value of the final component of our learning rule.
 The neuron receives direct current input in the presence of a reward or
 a punishment depending on the training method use and fires regularly at
 a rate.
 The dopamine concentration, D(t) which modulates synaptic change is a global
 eligibility trace that increases each time the dopamine neuron fires,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{dD(t)}{dt}=-\frac{D(t)}{\tau_{d}}+\sum_{k}\delta(t-t_{k}^{*}),
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Box Frameless
position "t"
hor_pos "c"
has_inner_box 1
inner_pos "t"
use_parbox 0
use_makebox 0
width "100col%"
special "none"
height "1in"
height_special "totalheight"
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
where 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{k}^{*}$
\end_inset

is the k-th DA spike and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 is the Dirac's delta.
 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{ij}$
\end_inset

 represents a temporal tag in synapses where pre-post firing occurs,
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\text{d}c_{ij}(t)}{\text{d}t}=-c_{ij}(t)/\tau_{c}-A_{-}x_{j}(t)S_{i}(t)-A_{-}y_{i}(t)S_{j}(t),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{-}$
\end_inset

 determines the amplitude of maximum depression that the synapse can undergo
 when presynaptic and postsynaptic spikes times occurr nearly at the same
 time.
 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{i}(t)$
\end_inset

 is the spike train of the i-th neuron, given by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
S_{i}(t)=\sum_{k}\delta(t-t_{i,k}^{*}),
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Box Frameless
position "t"
hor_pos "c"
has_inner_box 1
inner_pos "t"
use_parbox 0
use_makebox 0
width "100col%"
special "none"
height "1in"
height_special "totalheight"
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
where 
\begin_inset Formula $t{}_{i,k}^{*}$
\end_inset

 is the timing of the spike, where 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 is the i-th neuron and 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 is the index of the spike.
 The tag decreases when the postsynaptic neuron fires an action potential
 and depends on the timing of the last spike timings of the presynaptic
 neuron through the variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{j}(t)$
\end_inset

 which evolves accordingly to: 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{dx_{j}(t)}{dt}=-\frac{x_{j}(t)}{\tau_{-}}+S_{j}(t).
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Box Frameless
position "t"
hor_pos "c"
has_inner_box 1
inner_pos "t"
use_parbox 0
use_makebox 0
width "100col%"
special "none"
height "1in"
height_special "totalheight"
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Equally the tag also decreases when the presynaptic neuron fires an action
 potential, depending on the postsynaptic neuron activity through the variable
 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}(t)$
\end_inset

 given by
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{dy_{i}(t)}{dt}=-\frac{y_{i}(t)}{\tau_{-}}+S_{i}(t),
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Box Frameless
position "t"
hor_pos "c"
has_inner_box 1
inner_pos "t"
use_parbox 0
use_makebox 0
width "100col%"
special "none"
height "1in"
height_special "totalheight"
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{-}$
\end_inset

 is the characteristic time of the 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{j}$
\end_inset

 eligibility traces.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset space \hfill{}
\end_inset

