\begin_layout Section
Odour exposure protocol
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In our learning paradigm we require KCs and MBONs to spike, together with
 the presence of dopamine.
 Whole cell recordings have shown how KCs respond when exposed to an odour
 over 1 second, firing at approximately 3 Hz, compared to a spontaneous
 activity of approximately 0.1 Hz (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Turner:2008eo"

\end_inset

).
 We can not know if the KCs fire constantly at 3 Hz for the entire duration
 of appetitive or aversive conditioning or whether they adapt to the odour
 and return to spontaneous activity.
 It is however sufficient to show an odour for 2 seconds coincident with
 reward or punishment for learning to take place (Johannes Freisenbrug -
 personal correspondence).
 For this reason we showed the odour for 2 seconds in our training paradigm.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Results
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our experimental collaborator has shown that when calcium imaging the 
\begin_inset Formula $M4\beta'$
\end_inset

 neuron, the activity changed both after appetitive and after aversive training.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $MVP2$
\end_inset

 MBON is known to change its firing rate only after aversive training.
 We simulated the 
\begin_inset Formula $M4\beta'$
\end_inset

 and the 
\begin_inset Formula $MVP2$
\end_inset

 MBONs during these two scenarios to check the prediction 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mbox{Fig\,.\,3.2}$
\end_inset

) and visualized the coding space the two MBONs form (
\begin_inset Formula $Fig$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

3.1).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Odours have a balance of approach and retreat drive before training
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In our model the firing rate of the3 
\begin_inset Formula $M4\beta'$
\end_inset

  neuron determines the retreat drive of an odour, while the firing rate
 of the 
\begin_inset Formula $MVP2$
\end_inset

 MBON determines the drive to approach.
 We visualized the valence coding space by plotting their firing rates on
 two different axes (
\begin_inset Formula $Fig.\,3.1$
\end_inset

).
 Using our protocol we generated two different odours by creating stereotypical
 KC responses.
 MBONs had a balanced drive of approach and retreat before training, which
 is to say the firing rate of the 
\begin_inset Formula $M4\beta'$
\end_inset

  and 
\begin_inset Formula $MVP2$
\end_inset

 neurons are approximately equal (
\begin_inset Formula $Fig.3.1$
\end_inset

).
 Training an odour with appetitive reinforcement decreased their drive towards
 retreat while, training with aversive reinforcement both decreased their
 drive towards approach and increased their retreat drive.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang british
