\begin_layout Plain Layout
This figure shows the odor valence space coded by MBONs.
 The white line represents a perfect balance between retreat and approach
 drive corresponding to both MBONs populations firing at the same rate.
 The green area corresponds to a higher drive towards approach.
 Conversely, the red area corresponds to a higher retreat drive from MBONs.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Bi-directional change in firing rate can occur when dopamine depresses the
 KC-MBON synapses
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We simulated an appetitive and aversive training protocols by showing odours
 for 2 seconds.
 In the presence of dopamine.
 We monitored the plasticity was active at the KCs-MBONs synapses and how
 this affected odour response before and after learning.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We observed that during appetitive training KC-
\begin_inset Formula $M4\beta'$
\end_inset

  synaptic weights decreased (
\begin_inset Formula $Fig.\,3.2\,A,$
\end_inset

 ii).
 After learning, the response from the 
\begin_inset Formula $M4\beta'$
\end_inset

  neuron shows a decreased firing rate profile compared to the naive state
 (
\begin_inset Formula $Fig.\,3.2\,A$
\end_inset

 iii).
 The firing rate decreased by 5 Hz compared to the initial state.
 Conversely, aversive learning increased the response of the 
\begin_inset Formula $M4\beta'$
\end_inset

  neuron compared to the naive state (
\begin_inset Formula $Fig.\,3.2\,B$
\end_inset

 iii).
 This is due to the fact that the firing rate of the MPV2 neuron decreased
 (
\begin_inset Formula $Fig.\,3.2\,B\,iv$
\end_inset

), thus increasing the ratio of excitation to inhibition (
\begin_inset Formula $Fig\,.3.3$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To observe a change in the firing rate that qualitatively matched the experiment
al results (
\begin_inset Formula $Fig\,1.2\,B)$
\end_inset

 wee had to choose the strength of the inhibitory MVP2-
\begin_inset Formula $M4\beta'$
\end_inset

 synapse that increased the ratio of excitation to inhibition (
\begin_inset Formula $Fig.\,3.4)$
\end_inset

.
 The MBONs we modelled receive input from 100 KCs which fire at a rate of
 3 Hz.
 Every second they receive 300 excitatory spikes with an average weight
 of 1 nS.
 In comparison the 
\begin_inset Formula $M4\beta'$
\end_inset

  inhibiting MVP2 neuron fires at a rate of approximately 50 Hz.
 To obtain the increase in firing rate that qualitatively matches experimental
 results (
\begin_inset Formula $Fig\,1.2\,B)$
\end_inset

 we had to tune the weight of the inhibitory synapse to be twice as strong
 at the excitatory synapse.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The odour representation in valence space moves perpendicularly to the line
 of equal drive and thus has a strong affect, whereas appetitive training
 moves along a single axis.
 This can be explained due to the fact that aversive learning both decreases
 drive to the approach MBON and increase drive to the retreat MBON.
 
\end_layout

