\begin_layout Section
Inhibition between MBONs can enhance odour discrimination
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
!Discuss the actual amount of excitation and inhibition coming in
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
! 300 spikes with an average weight of 1 nS compared to 50 spikes with an
 average weight of 2 nS.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
!
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To show that the MVP2-M4 inhibitory synapse is necessary and that it enhances
 discrimination we performed the simulation in two conditions, once with
 the MVP2-M4 inhibitory synapse active (
\begin_inset Formula $Fig.3.5A$
\end_inset

) and once without (
\begin_inset Formula $Fig.\,3.5\,B$
\end_inset

).
 The M4 MBON increases its firing rate only when there is an inhibitory
 synapse between the MVP2 and M4 Furthermore, if we look at the valence
 coding space (Figure 9 bottom), we observe that the inhibitory synapse
 between the MBON increases discriminability by pushing the representation
 deeper into the retreat area (
\begin_inset Formula $Fig.3.5B$
\end_inset

 bottom).
 
\end_layout

