\begin_layout Section
Trained odour can change the valence of a similar untrained odour 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Based on evidence that similar odour activates an overlapping subset of
 KCs in the MB we tested in our mnodel how learning affects untrained odours
 on our model.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have selected two odours with 50% overlap in the identity of KCs activated
 two mimic similar odours that appear in nature.
 In the naive state, both of the odours have a neutral valence (
\begin_inset Formula $Fig3.6$
\end_inset

).
 We subsequently trained, the first odour with both appetitive and aversive
 reinforcement.
 When we tested both of the two odurs for their response in the MBON code
 space we observed that both odours have changed the valence to that of
 the trained odour (
\begin_inset Formula $Fig.\,3.6$
\end_inset

) which has been shown experimentally to occurr (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Campbell:2013fba"

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
LIMITATION mechanism of learning even when learning is not present in order
 to stabilize untrained representations.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

