\begin_layout Chapter
Discussion and future work
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Conclusions from preliminary results
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have begun to explore how sparse odour information stored in a balanced
 spiking network can be read by the MBONs through a multifactor learning
 rule.
 We have used recent evidence that suggests that approach MBONs inhibit
 retreat MBONs (David Owald - personal communication) and have shown that
 MBON-to-MBON inhibition can lead to enhanced discrimination (
\begin_inset Formula $Fig3.4$
\end_inset

).
 Enhanced discrimination is a property that is useful for a system classifying
 odours, thus it could be possible that there are retreat biasing MBONs
 that inhibit approach biasing MBONs.
 If this is true than both aversive and appetitive learning would induce
 bi-directional changes of firing rate into subsets of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

approach
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 MBONs and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

retreat
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 MBONs.
 In our model we tested bi-directional change that occurrs only during aversive
 learning.
 In such a scenario, we predict that training the same odour successively
 with both aversive and appetitive reinforcement would change the valence
 from appetitive to aversive if the odour was trained appetitive first and
 keep the valence aversive if aversive training occurred first.
 Our results suggest that in the fruit fly good odour memories with are
 easier to convert into bad memories and bad memories are more resilient.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have visualized the coding space created by the firing rates of the MBONs
 create in response to an odour.
 The valence space was inspired by experimental evidence that shows the
 highest degree of separation in terms of MBON firing rates is when odours
 have different valances rather than different identities (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Hige:2015er"

\end_inset

).
 While MBONs may be very good at separating odours based on their valences
 it could be possible that other information could be stored in the spike
 times of the MBONs, such as information about odour identity or qualitative
 factors such as what kind of reward the odour predicts: water, food, mating.
 It is also worth noting that the experimental paradigm uses simple stimuli
 to train the fly which might restrict the ability of the neuron to learn
 complex interactions.
 For example we know that the flies are capable to associate an odour that
 predicts another odour that predicts reward which is called second ordour
 conditioning (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Wu:2007ie"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Future work
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Learning over larger periods of time
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have modelled two dopaminergic neurons in our model one for each learning
 scenario: appetitive and aversive.
 The dopaminergic neurons create a temporal window in which plasticity can
 depress a synapse.
 The time window during which coincidence spikes and dopamine presence can
 depress a synapse is 20 ms in our model.
 However, there is evidence that the outcome of learning depends on the
 timing of the odour and the punishment over larger intervals of time (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Yarali:2008dt"

\end_inset

) A fly that is shown an odour first and shocked 15 s later will learn to
 avoid the odour (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Yarali:2008dt"

\end_inset

).
 If the sequence is reversed and a fly is shocked first the odour will become
 appetitive (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Yarali:2008dt"

\end_inset

).
 Furthermore if a fly is shocked with a strong shock first paired with an
 odour and a milder shock later paired with a different odour the fly will
 learn to approach the second odour (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Perisse:2013fp"

\end_inset

).
 Our model fails to replicate these results that belongs to the paradigm
 of relief learning because the shock signal always leads to depression
 of the approach pathway in our model.
 One possible solution to this problem could be that the activity of appetitive
 and aversive dopaminergic neurons is relative to past experiences.
 In our model we can test a paradigm, where when we would stop a shock signal
 after a period of time, the aversive dopaminergic neurons will decrease
 their activity and the appetitive dopaminergic neurons will show an increase
 in their activity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Second order conditioning
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In our first model investigating plasticity in the MB we have used a learning
 rule that leads to synaptic depression when dopamine in present (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Greenspan:2004iu"

\end_inset

).
 However, the fly is able to learn to approach an odour that predicts another
 appetitive trained odour.
 This could be because during second order conditioning when the fly is
 exposed to the appetitive odour, appetitive dopaminergic neurons increase
 their activity which makes the fly susceptible to learn to consider the
 second odour as being appetitive.
 We would like to explore how we can tune the activity of dopaminergic neurons
 in response to not only reward and punishment but also odour stimuli such
 as odours.
 A candidate mechanism that could explain this might be the feedback loop
 from MBONs to DAs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Implementing the MBON - DA feedback loop
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have begun preliminary work on investigating the MBON - DA feedback loop.
 Recent anatomical work shown that the 
\begin_inset Formula $M4\beta'$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

retreat
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 biasing MBON has axons projecting to appetitive DA neurons 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Owald:2015cn"

\end_inset

.
 We would like to examine the functional consequences that such a feedback
 loop has to learning and test different scenarios - what happens when the
 feedback loop is excitatory or inhibitory.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
State dependent memory retrieval 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our experimental collaborator has recently shown that the approach MVP2
 output neuron increases its response to an odour when the fruit fly is
 hungry (
\begin_inset Formula $Fig\,1.3$
\end_inset

).
 This implies that the olfactory circuit is modulated by the behavioural
 state of the organism.
 A plausible mechanism which has been explored in cortex is inhibition,
 which has been linked to brain states such as attention (Harris and Thiele
 2011, Stringer et al., 2015 ).
 We would like to explore how inhibition in the MB changes in response to
 motivational state.
 A candidate neuron mechanism might be APL state dependent inhibition, which
 is a neuron that inhibits the entire population of KCs (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Lin:2014io"

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

